data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with **ThreadAbortException as control flow**. Here's the complete migration:

## Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — there's no way to forcibly kill a managed thread. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Wrap work in a Task so we can race it against a timeout
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Block until the task completes or the timeout fires
            task.Wait(token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Wait unwraps faulted tasks as AggregateException — 
        // preserves original behavior
        return task.Result;
    }
}
```

## If the `Func<T>` is long-running and must cooperate

The critical paradigm shift: **cancellation is cooperative now**. If `work()` runs a tight loop or blocks on I/O, it won't stop just because the token fired. You need to pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        task.Wait(token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }

    return task.Result;
}
```

Callers then check the token:
```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **Work ignores the token** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation won't interrupt a blocking `Thread.Sleep` or tight CPU loop. Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Add `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` in loops. |
| **Forgetting `using` on CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable` — leaking it leaks internal timers. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level orchestration point (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`). Don't suppress it deeper in the call chain. |
| **Uncooperative 3rd-party code** | If you can't modify the work to check a token, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. This is the only safe way to forcibly stop uncooperative code. |
| **`task.Result` after cancellation** | Access `.Result` only after confirming the task completed successfully, otherwise it throws `AggregateException`. The code above handles this correctly since the `catch` rethrows before reaching `.Result`. |
